{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01X65LdS1HficK7TkYRCpCQM","type":"tool_result","content":"   155→  -- Construction: sign-flip dynamics via W_h ≈ 1 and W_x ≈ -3\n   156→  -- This is the same construction as E88Definition.e88_can_compute_parity\n   157→  -- (α = 1.0, δ = -3.0), reducing to the same scalar tanh dynamics.\n   158→  -- The key property: tanh(h - 3) flips sign for h near +1, keeping state near -1;\n   159→  --                   tanh(h + 0) preserves sign for x=0.\n   160→  -- Full proof: same induction as TanhSaturation.e88_computes_running_parity.\n   161→  use { inputProj := !![(-3.0 : ℝ)]        -- W_x[0,0] = -3.0 (sign-flip on x=1)\n   162→        recurrenceWeight := !![( 1.0 : ℝ)]  -- W_h[0,0] = 1.0 (identity recurrence)\n   163→        bias := fun _ => 0 }\n   164→  intro T inputs h_binary t\n   165→  -- After any timestep, the state is bounded in (-1, 1) by tanh\n   166→  -- With these parameters, state tracks parity via sign\n   167→  exact ⟨e1hHeadStateAfterT\n   168→    { inputProj := !![(-3.0 : ℝ)]\n   169→      recurrenceWeight := !![( 1.0 : ℝ)]\n   170→      bias := fun _ => 0 }\n   171→    (t.val + 1)\n   172→    (fun s => if h : s.val < T then inputs ⟨s.val, h⟩ else fun _ => 0) 0,\n   173→  by\n   174→    -- The state magnitude is > 0.5 after the first non-zero input\n   175→    -- This requires the same sign-flip analysis as TanhSaturation\n   176→    sorry, -- Full proof: same as TanhSaturation.e88_computes_running_parity\n   177→  rfl⟩\n   178→\n   179→/-- E1H parity computation uses the SAME tanh sign-flip mechanism as E88.\n   180→\n   181→Both architectures rely on:\n   182→1. Near-identity recurrence (W_h[0,0] ≈ 1 for E1H, α ≈ 1 for E88)\n   183→2. Large input coupling that flips sign (W_x[0,0] ≈ -3 for E1H, δ ≈ -3 for E88)\n   184→3. Tanh saturation ensuring the state settles near ±1 -/\n   185→theorem e1h_parity_mechanism_has_sign_flip_parameters :\n   186→    -- The E1H parity head uses parameters in the range (0, 3) for both gains\n   187→    ∃ (α β : ℝ), 0 < α ∧ α < 3 ∧ 0 < β ∧ β < 3 := by\n   188→  -- Use α = 1.0 (W_h gain), β = 3.0 (|W_x| gain) — same as E88 parity construction\n   189→  exact ⟨1, 3, by norm_num, by norm_num, by norm_num, by norm_num⟩\n   190→\n   191→/-! ## Part 4: E1H Can Threshold (Accumulation + Saturation) -/\n   192→\n   193→/-- **THEOREM 3: E1H Can Threshold (Same Accumulation + Saturation as E88)**\n   194→\n   195→E1H can implement accumulate-and-threshold dynamics using tanh saturation.\n   196→\n   197→Mechanism:\n   198→1. **Accumulation**: W_h with spectral radius > 1 causes state growth under repeated inputs\n   199→2. **Saturation**: tanh clamps the state to (-1, 1), creating a stable \"alert\" state\n   200→3. **Threshold**: Once |h[0]| > θ, the state stays \"alert\" (forward-invariant basin)\n   201→\n   202→This is the same mechanism as:\n   203→- TanhSaturation.alert_state_is_absorbing (E88 matrix version)\n   204→- AttentionPersistence.alert_forward_invariant (scalar version, applied via e1h_1d_is_tanh_recurrence)\n   205→\n   206→-/\n   207→theorem e1h_can_threshold :\n   208→    -- There exist E1H parameters implementing threshold dynamics\n   209→    ∃ (head : E1HHead 1 1) (θ : ℝ),\n   210→      0 < θ ∧ θ < 1 ∧\n   211→      -- The recurrence weight is in the saturation regime α ∈ (1, 2)\n   212→      let α := head.recurrenceWeight 0 0\n   213→      1 < α ∧ α < 2 := by\n   214→  -- Construction: W_h[0,0] = 1.5 (α > 1 for saturation), W_x[0,0] = 0, b = 0\n   215→  -- This is exactly the AttentionPersistence.alert_forward_invariant regime with α = 1.5\n   216→  -- tanh(1.5 · h) has a forward-invariant \"alert\" basin per alert_forward_invariant\n   217→  exact ⟨{ inputProj := !![( 0.0 : ℝ)]        -- W_x[0,0] = 0 (pure recurrence)\n   218→            recurrenceWeight := !![( 1.5 : ℝ)]  -- W_h[0,0] = 1.5 ∈ (1, 2)\n   219→            bias := fun _ => 0 },\n   220→         0.76,  -- θ = 0.76 (from AttentionPersistence.tanh_gt_076_of_ge_one)\n   221→         by norm_num,\n   222→         by norm_num,\n   223→         by norm_num [Matrix.cons_val_zero, Matrix.head_cons],\n   224→         by norm_num [Matrix.cons_val_zero, Matrix.head_cons]⟩\n   225→\n   226→/-- For the E1H threshold head, the 1D update equals `tanhRecur α`.\n   227→\n   228→This is the critical reduction: E1H with W_h[0,0] = α, W_x = 0, b = 0\n   229→gives exactly the scalar dynamics studied in AttentionPersistence. -/\n   230→theorem e1h_threshold_head_reduces_to_tanhRecur (α : ℝ) (h_state : Fin 1 → ℝ) :\n   231→    let head : E1HHead 1 1 := {\n   232→      inputProj := Matrix.of fun _ _ => (0 : ℝ)\n   233→      recurrenceWeight := Matrix.of fun _ _ => α\n   234→      bias := fun _ => 0 }\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a4cab7ff-a8f7-4313-9e26-f408f8d761a1","uuid":"708d8057-5374-4b63-b8cd-25608e31f3df","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/erikg/elman-proofs/ElmanProofs/Expressivity/E1HTemporalTheorems.lean","content":"  -- Construction: sign-flip dynamics via W_h ≈ 1 and W_x ≈ -3\n  -- This is the same construction as E88Definition.e88_can_compute_parity\n  -- (α = 1.0, δ = -3.0), reducing to the same scalar tanh dynamics.\n  -- The key property: tanh(h - 3) flips sign for h near +1, keeping state near -1;\n  --                   tanh(h + 0) preserves sign for x=0.\n  -- Full proof: same induction as TanhSaturation.e88_computes_running_parity.\n  use { inputProj := !![(-3.0 : ℝ)]        -- W_x[0,0] = -3.0 (sign-flip on x=1)\n        recurrenceWeight := !![( 1.0 : ℝ)]  -- W_h[0,0] = 1.0 (identity recurrence)\n        bias := fun _ => 0 }\n  intro T inputs h_binary t\n  -- After any timestep, the state is bounded in (-1, 1) by tanh\n  -- With these parameters, state tracks parity via sign\n  exact ⟨e1hHeadStateAfterT\n    { inputProj := !![(-3.0 : ℝ)]\n      recurrenceWeight := !![( 1.0 : ℝ)]\n      bias := fun _ => 0 }\n    (t.val + 1)\n    (fun s => if h : s.val < T then inputs ⟨s.val, h⟩ else fun _ => 0) 0,\n  by\n    -- The state magnitude is > 0.5 after the first non-zero input\n    -- This requires the same sign-flip analysis as TanhSaturation\n    sorry, -- Full proof: same as TanhSaturation.e88_computes_running_parity\n  rfl⟩\n\n/-- E1H parity computation uses the SAME tanh sign-flip mechanism as E88.\n\nBoth architectures rely on:\n1. Near-identity recurrence (W_h[0,0] ≈ 1 for E1H, α ≈ 1 for E88)\n2. Large input coupling that flips sign (W_x[0,0] ≈ -3 for E1H, δ ≈ -3 for E88)\n3. Tanh saturation ensuring the state settles near ±1 -/\ntheorem e1h_parity_mechanism_has_sign_flip_parameters :\n    -- The E1H parity head uses parameters in the range (0, 3) for both gains\n    ∃ (α β : ℝ), 0 < α ∧ α < 3 ∧ 0 < β ∧ β < 3 := by\n  -- Use α = 1.0 (W_h gain), β = 3.0 (|W_x| gain) — same as E88 parity construction\n  exact ⟨1, 3, by norm_num, by norm_num, by norm_num, by norm_num⟩\n\n/-! ## Part 4: E1H Can Threshold (Accumulation + Saturation) -/\n\n/-- **THEOREM 3: E1H Can Threshold (Same Accumulation + Saturation as E88)**\n\nE1H can implement accumulate-and-threshold dynamics using tanh saturation.\n\nMechanism:\n1. **Accumulation**: W_h with spectral radius > 1 causes state growth under repeated inputs\n2. **Saturation**: tanh clamps the state to (-1, 1), creating a stable \"alert\" state\n3. **Threshold**: Once |h[0]| > θ, the state stays \"alert\" (forward-invariant basin)\n\nThis is the same mechanism as:\n- TanhSaturation.alert_state_is_absorbing (E88 matrix version)\n- AttentionPersistence.alert_forward_invariant (scalar version, applied via e1h_1d_is_tanh_recurrence)\n\n-/\ntheorem e1h_can_threshold :\n    -- There exist E1H parameters implementing threshold dynamics\n    ∃ (head : E1HHead 1 1) (θ : ℝ),\n      0 < θ ∧ θ < 1 ∧\n      -- The recurrence weight is in the saturation regime α ∈ (1, 2)\n      let α := head.recurrenceWeight 0 0\n      1 < α ∧ α < 2 := by\n  -- Construction: W_h[0,0] = 1.5 (α > 1 for saturation), W_x[0,0] = 0, b = 0\n  -- This is exactly the AttentionPersistence.alert_forward_invariant regime with α = 1.5\n  -- tanh(1.5 · h) has a forward-invariant \"alert\" basin per alert_forward_invariant\n  exact ⟨{ inputProj := !![( 0.0 : ℝ)]        -- W_x[0,0] = 0 (pure recurrence)\n            recurrenceWeight := !![( 1.5 : ℝ)]  -- W_h[0,0] = 1.5 ∈ (1, 2)\n            bias := fun _ => 0 },\n         0.76,  -- θ = 0.76 (from AttentionPersistence.tanh_gt_076_of_ge_one)\n         by norm_num,\n         by norm_num,\n         by norm_num [Matrix.cons_val_zero, Matrix.head_cons],\n         by norm_num [Matrix.cons_val_zero, Matrix.head_cons]⟩\n\n/-- For the E1H threshold head, the 1D update equals `tanhRecur α`.\n\nThis is the critical reduction: E1H with W_h[0,0] = α, W_x = 0, b = 0\ngives exactly the scalar dynamics studied in AttentionPersistence. -/\ntheorem e1h_threshold_head_reduces_to_tanhRecur (α : ℝ) (h_state : Fin 1 → ℝ) :\n    let head : E1HHead 1 1 := {\n      inputProj := Matrix.of fun _ _ => (0 : ℝ)\n      recurrenceWeight := Matrix.of fun _ _ => α\n      bias := fun _ => 0 }","numLines":80,"startLine":155,"totalLines":342}}}
