{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_017rH4y5mE8SPBLR7854QnsX","type":"tool_result","content":"   230→theorem e1h_threshold_head_reduces_to_tanhRecur (α : ℝ) (h_state : Fin 1 → ℝ) :\n   231→    let head : E1HHead 1 1 := {\n   232→      inputProj := Matrix.of fun _ _ => (0 : ℝ)\n   233→      recurrenceWeight := Matrix.of fun _ _ => α\n   234→      bias := fun _ => 0 }\n   235→    e1hHeadUpdate head h_state (fun _ => 0) 0 =\n   236→    AttentionPersistence.tanhRecur α (h_state 0) := by\n   237→  simp only [e1hHeadUpdate, vecTanh, AttentionPersistence.tanhRecur]\n   238→  congr 1\n   239→  simp [Matrix.mulVec, Matrix.dotProduct, Fin.sum_univ_one, Matrix.of_apply]\n   240→\n   241→/-- Once an E1H state exceeds the alert threshold, it stays there.\n   242→\n   243→This follows directly from AttentionPersistence.alert_forward_invariant, applied via\n   244→the 1D reduction e1h_threshold_head_reduces_to_tanhRecur. -/\n   245→theorem e1h_alert_state_forward_invariant (α : ℝ) (hα_lo : 1 < α) (hα_hi : α < 2)\n   246→    (θ : ℝ) (hθ_pos : 0 < θ) (hθ_lt : θ < 0.8)\n   247→    (h_state : Fin 1 → ℝ) (h_alert : AttentionPersistence.isAlert (h_state 0) θ) :\n   248→    let head : E1HHead 1 1 := {\n   249→      inputProj := Matrix.of fun _ _ => (0 : ℝ)\n   250→      recurrenceWeight := Matrix.of fun _ _ => α\n   251→      bias := fun _ => 0 }\n   252→    AttentionPersistence.isAlert (e1hHeadUpdate head h_state (fun _ => 0) 0) θ := by\n   253→  -- Step 1: reduce E1H update to tanhRecur via the 1D correspondence\n   254→  rw [e1h_threshold_head_reduces_to_tanhRecur]\n   255→  -- Step 2: apply AttentionPersistence.alert_forward_invariant\n   256→  exact AttentionPersistence.alert_forward_invariant α θ hα_lo hθ_pos hθ_lt\n   257→    (Set.mem_def.mpr h_alert)\n   258→\n   259→/-! ## Part 5: E1H Heads Evolve Independently -/\n   260→\n   261→/-- **THEOREM 4: E1H Heads Evolve Independently**\n   262→\n   263→Each E1H head's temporal dynamics are fully independent of other heads.\n   264→This is the same structural property as E88's head independence.\n   265→\n   266→Both E1H and E88 have this property because:\n   267→1. Each head has its own parameters\n   268→2. Multi-head evolution computes each head independently: no shared state\n   269→3. Changing one head's parameters does not affect another head's trajectory\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a4cab7ff-a8f7-4313-9e26-f408f8d761a1","uuid":"a65489e2-a13d-486c-81cc-066267f271aa","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/erikg/elman-proofs/ElmanProofs/Expressivity/E1HTemporalTheorems.lean","content":"theorem e1h_threshold_head_reduces_to_tanhRecur (α : ℝ) (h_state : Fin 1 → ℝ) :\n    let head : E1HHead 1 1 := {\n      inputProj := Matrix.of fun _ _ => (0 : ℝ)\n      recurrenceWeight := Matrix.of fun _ _ => α\n      bias := fun _ => 0 }\n    e1hHeadUpdate head h_state (fun _ => 0) 0 =\n    AttentionPersistence.tanhRecur α (h_state 0) := by\n  simp only [e1hHeadUpdate, vecTanh, AttentionPersistence.tanhRecur]\n  congr 1\n  simp [Matrix.mulVec, Matrix.dotProduct, Fin.sum_univ_one, Matrix.of_apply]\n\n/-- Once an E1H state exceeds the alert threshold, it stays there.\n\nThis follows directly from AttentionPersistence.alert_forward_invariant, applied via\nthe 1D reduction e1h_threshold_head_reduces_to_tanhRecur. -/\ntheorem e1h_alert_state_forward_invariant (α : ℝ) (hα_lo : 1 < α) (hα_hi : α < 2)\n    (θ : ℝ) (hθ_pos : 0 < θ) (hθ_lt : θ < 0.8)\n    (h_state : Fin 1 → ℝ) (h_alert : AttentionPersistence.isAlert (h_state 0) θ) :\n    let head : E1HHead 1 1 := {\n      inputProj := Matrix.of fun _ _ => (0 : ℝ)\n      recurrenceWeight := Matrix.of fun _ _ => α\n      bias := fun _ => 0 }\n    AttentionPersistence.isAlert (e1hHeadUpdate head h_state (fun _ => 0) 0) θ := by\n  -- Step 1: reduce E1H update to tanhRecur via the 1D correspondence\n  rw [e1h_threshold_head_reduces_to_tanhRecur]\n  -- Step 2: apply AttentionPersistence.alert_forward_invariant\n  exact AttentionPersistence.alert_forward_invariant α θ hα_lo hθ_pos hθ_lt\n    (Set.mem_def.mpr h_alert)\n\n/-! ## Part 5: E1H Heads Evolve Independently -/\n\n/-- **THEOREM 4: E1H Heads Evolve Independently**\n\nEach E1H head's temporal dynamics are fully independent of other heads.\nThis is the same structural property as E88's head independence.\n\nBoth E1H and E88 have this property because:\n1. Each head has its own parameters\n2. Multi-head evolution computes each head independently: no shared state\n3. Changing one head's parameters does not affect another head's trajectory","numLines":40,"startLine":230,"totalLines":342}}}
