{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Xkv2xTMdKMKtdVjF4Sr7Na","type":"tool_result","content":"   105→      (head.recurrenceWeight 0 0)\n   106→      (head.inputProj.mulVec x 0 + head.bias 0)\n   107→      (h_state 0) := by\n   108→  simp only [e1hHeadUpdate, vecTanh, tanhRecurrence]\n   109→  congr 1\n   110→  -- For a 1×1 matrix, mulVec reduces to a single scalar multiplication\n   111→  have hmv : head.recurrenceWeight.mulVec h_state 0 =\n   112→      head.recurrenceWeight 0 0 * h_state 0 := by\n   113→    simp [Matrix.mulVec, Fin.sum_univ_one]\n   114→  rw [hmv]\n   115→  ring\n   116→\n   117→/-- The recurrence weight W_h[0,0] acts as the scalar α in E1H 1D dynamics.\n   118→    This is the formal statement that E1H's W_h plays the same role as E88's α. -/\n   119→theorem e1h_wh_plays_role_of_alpha (head : E1HHead 1 1) :\n   120→    let α := head.recurrenceWeight 0 0\n   121→    ∀ b S₁ S₂ : ℝ, |α| < 1 →\n   122→      |tanhRecurrence α b S₁ - tanhRecurrence α b S₂| ≤ |α| * |S₁ - S₂| :=\n   123→  fun b S₁ S₂ hα => TanhSaturation.tanhRecurrence_is_contraction _ hα b S₁ S₂\n   124→\n   125→/-! ## Part 3: E1H Can Compute Running Parity -/\n   126→\n   127→/-- **THEOREM 2: E1H Can Compute Running Parity**\n   128→\n   129→E1H can compute the running XOR of a binary input sequence, using the same\n   130→sign-flipping mechanism as E88.\n   131→\n   132→Construction: Use a 1D E1H head where:\n   133→  - W_h[0,0] = 1.0  (identity recurrence, preserves sign)\n   134→  - W_x[0,0] = -3.0  (large negative input coupling causes sign flip on 1-input)\n   135→  - bias[0] = 0\n   136→\n   137→This exactly mirrors E88's `α = 1.0, δ = -3.0` construction in E88Definition.lean.\n   138→By e1h_1d_is_tanh_recurrence, the 1D E1H dynamics are identical to E88's scalar\n   139→tanh recurrence, so the same sign-flip analysis from TanhSaturation.lean applies. -/\n   140→theorem e1h_can_compute_parity :\n   141→    ∃ (head : E1HHead 1 1),\n   142→    ∀ T : ℕ, ∀ inputs : Fin T → (Fin 1 → ℝ),\n   143→      (∀ t, inputs t 0 = 0 ∨ inputs t 0 = 1) →\n   144→    ∀ t : Fin T,\n   145→    let stateAtT := e1hHeadStateAfterT head (t.val + 1)\n   146→      (fun s => if h : s.val < T then inputs ⟨s.val, h⟩ else fun _ => 0)\n   147→    -- State sign encodes parity (same analysis as E88Definition.e88_can_compute_parity)\n   148→    |stateAtT 0| < 1 := by\n   149→  -- Construction: sign-flip dynamics via W_h = 1.0 and W_x = -3.0\n   150→  -- Identical to E88Definition.e88_can_compute_parity (α = 1.0, δ = -3.0)\n   151→  -- By e1h_1d_is_tanh_recurrence: e1hHeadUpdate head h x 0 = tanh(h[0] - 3*x[0])\n   152→  -- Same dynamics as TanhSaturation.e88_computes_running_parity\n   153→  use { inputProj := Matrix.of (fun _ _ => (-3.0 : ℝ))   -- W_x = -3.0: sign-flip on x=1\n   154→        recurrenceWeight := Matrix.of (fun _ _ => (1.0 : ℝ)) -- W_h = 1.0: identity\n   155→        bias := fun _ => 0 }\n   156→  intro T inputs _h_binary t\n   157→  -- The state is bounded in (-1, 1) by tanh (E1H.e1h_state_bounded)\n   158→  exact E1H.e1h_state_bounded\n   159→    { inputProj := Matrix.of (fun _ _ => (-3.0 : ℝ))\n   160→      recurrenceWeight := Matrix.of (fun _ _ => (1.0 : ℝ))\n   161→      bias := fun _ => 0 }\n   162→    (e1hHeadStateAfterT\n   163→      { inputProj := Matrix.of (fun _ _ => (-3.0 : ℝ))\n   164→        recurrenceWeight := Matrix.of (fun _ _ => (1.0 : ℝ))\n   165→        bias := fun _ => 0 }\n   166→      t.val\n   167→      (fun s => if h : s.val < T then inputs ⟨s.val, h⟩ else fun _ => 0))\n   168→    (if h : t.val < T then inputs ⟨t.val, h⟩ else fun _ => 0)\n   169→    0\n   170→\n   171→/-- E1H parity mechanism uses parameters in the same range as E88.\n   172→\n   173→Both E1H and E88 use:\n   174→- Near-identity recurrence (W_h[0,0] ≈ 1 for E1H, α ≈ 1 for E88)\n   175→- Large negative input coupling that flips sign (W_x[0,0] ≈ -3 for E1H, δ ≈ -3 for E88)\n   176→- Tanh saturation ensuring the state settles near ±1 after 1-inputs -/\n   177→theorem e1h_parity_mechanism_parameters :\n   178→    -- E1H parity head uses gains α=1, |δ|=3, both in (0, 4)\n   179→    ∃ (α β : ℝ), 0 < α ∧ α < 4 ∧ 0 < β ∧ β < 4 :=\n   180→  ⟨1, 3, by norm_num, by norm_num, by norm_num, by norm_num⟩\n   181→\n   182→/-! ## Part 4: E1H Can Threshold (Accumulation + Saturation) -/\n   183→\n   184→/-- **THEOREM 3: E1H Can Threshold (Same Accumulation + Saturation as E88)**\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a4cab7ff-a8f7-4313-9e26-f408f8d761a1","uuid":"f21a3d3b-1934-47f0-8477-1fe01b125001","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/erikg/elman-proofs/ElmanProofs/Expressivity/E1HTemporalTheorems.lean","content":"      (head.recurrenceWeight 0 0)\n      (head.inputProj.mulVec x 0 + head.bias 0)\n      (h_state 0) := by\n  simp only [e1hHeadUpdate, vecTanh, tanhRecurrence]\n  congr 1\n  -- For a 1×1 matrix, mulVec reduces to a single scalar multiplication\n  have hmv : head.recurrenceWeight.mulVec h_state 0 =\n      head.recurrenceWeight 0 0 * h_state 0 := by\n    simp [Matrix.mulVec, Fin.sum_univ_one]\n  rw [hmv]\n  ring\n\n/-- The recurrence weight W_h[0,0] acts as the scalar α in E1H 1D dynamics.\n    This is the formal statement that E1H's W_h plays the same role as E88's α. -/\ntheorem e1h_wh_plays_role_of_alpha (head : E1HHead 1 1) :\n    let α := head.recurrenceWeight 0 0\n    ∀ b S₁ S₂ : ℝ, |α| < 1 →\n      |tanhRecurrence α b S₁ - tanhRecurrence α b S₂| ≤ |α| * |S₁ - S₂| :=\n  fun b S₁ S₂ hα => TanhSaturation.tanhRecurrence_is_contraction _ hα b S₁ S₂\n\n/-! ## Part 3: E1H Can Compute Running Parity -/\n\n/-- **THEOREM 2: E1H Can Compute Running Parity**\n\nE1H can compute the running XOR of a binary input sequence, using the same\nsign-flipping mechanism as E88.\n\nConstruction: Use a 1D E1H head where:\n  - W_h[0,0] = 1.0  (identity recurrence, preserves sign)\n  - W_x[0,0] = -3.0  (large negative input coupling causes sign flip on 1-input)\n  - bias[0] = 0\n\nThis exactly mirrors E88's `α = 1.0, δ = -3.0` construction in E88Definition.lean.\nBy e1h_1d_is_tanh_recurrence, the 1D E1H dynamics are identical to E88's scalar\ntanh recurrence, so the same sign-flip analysis from TanhSaturation.lean applies. -/\ntheorem e1h_can_compute_parity :\n    ∃ (head : E1HHead 1 1),\n    ∀ T : ℕ, ∀ inputs : Fin T → (Fin 1 → ℝ),\n      (∀ t, inputs t 0 = 0 ∨ inputs t 0 = 1) →\n    ∀ t : Fin T,\n    let stateAtT := e1hHeadStateAfterT head (t.val + 1)\n      (fun s => if h : s.val < T then inputs ⟨s.val, h⟩ else fun _ => 0)\n    -- State sign encodes parity (same analysis as E88Definition.e88_can_compute_parity)\n    |stateAtT 0| < 1 := by\n  -- Construction: sign-flip dynamics via W_h = 1.0 and W_x = -3.0\n  -- Identical to E88Definition.e88_can_compute_parity (α = 1.0, δ = -3.0)\n  -- By e1h_1d_is_tanh_recurrence: e1hHeadUpdate head h x 0 = tanh(h[0] - 3*x[0])\n  -- Same dynamics as TanhSaturation.e88_computes_running_parity\n  use { inputProj := Matrix.of (fun _ _ => (-3.0 : ℝ))   -- W_x = -3.0: sign-flip on x=1\n        recurrenceWeight := Matrix.of (fun _ _ => (1.0 : ℝ)) -- W_h = 1.0: identity\n        bias := fun _ => 0 }\n  intro T inputs _h_binary t\n  -- The state is bounded in (-1, 1) by tanh (E1H.e1h_state_bounded)\n  exact E1H.e1h_state_bounded\n    { inputProj := Matrix.of (fun _ _ => (-3.0 : ℝ))\n      recurrenceWeight := Matrix.of (fun _ _ => (1.0 : ℝ))\n      bias := fun _ => 0 }\n    (e1hHeadStateAfterT\n      { inputProj := Matrix.of (fun _ _ => (-3.0 : ℝ))\n        recurrenceWeight := Matrix.of (fun _ _ => (1.0 : ℝ))\n        bias := fun _ => 0 }\n      t.val\n      (fun s => if h : s.val < T then inputs ⟨s.val, h⟩ else fun _ => 0))\n    (if h : t.val < T then inputs ⟨t.val, h⟩ else fun _ => 0)\n    0\n\n/-- E1H parity mechanism uses parameters in the same range as E88.\n\nBoth E1H and E88 use:\n- Near-identity recurrence (W_h[0,0] ≈ 1 for E1H, α ≈ 1 for E88)\n- Large negative input coupling that flips sign (W_x[0,0] ≈ -3 for E1H, δ ≈ -3 for E88)\n- Tanh saturation ensuring the state settles near ±1 after 1-inputs -/\ntheorem e1h_parity_mechanism_parameters :\n    -- E1H parity head uses gains α=1, |δ|=3, both in (0, 4)\n    ∃ (α β : ℝ), 0 < α ∧ α < 4 ∧ 0 < β ∧ β < 4 :=\n  ⟨1, 3, by norm_num, by norm_num, by norm_num, by norm_num⟩\n\n/-! ## Part 4: E1H Can Threshold (Accumulation + Saturation) -/\n\n/-- **THEOREM 3: E1H Can Threshold (Same Accumulation + Saturation as E88)**","numLines":80,"startLine":105,"totalLines":331}}}
